# Utility Function Naming Conventions

## File Naming Standards
- **Utility function files must use camelCase**: `handleNumericInput.ts`
- **File name must match the exported function name exactly** (except for extension)
- **Never use PascalCase for utility files** - PascalCase is reserved for React components

## Function Naming Standards
- **Utility functions must use camelCase**: `handleNumericInput()`
- **Function name must match the file name** for consistency and discoverability

## Examples

### ✅ Correct Patterns
```
src/utils/handleNumericInput.ts
export function handleNumericInput() { ... }

src/utils/parseNumber.ts
export function parseNumber() { ... }

src/utils/convertToEuro.ts
export function convertToEuro() { ... }
```

### ❌ Incorrect Patterns
```
src/utils/handleNumericInput.ts  // PascalCase file name
export function handleNumericInput() { ... }

src/utils/handle-numeric-input.ts  // kebab-case file name
export function handleNumericInput() { ... }

src/utils/handleNumericInput.ts
export function HandleNumericInput() { ... }  // PascalCase function name
```

## Import Standards
- Import utility functions using the same camelCase name as the file
- Use relative imports for utilities in the same directory
- Use absolute imports with path aliases for utilities in other directories

### Import Examples
```typescript
// ✅ Correct imports
import { handleNumericInput } from "./handleNumericInput";
import { parseNumber } from "utils/parseNumber";
import convertToEuro from "utils/convertToEuro";

// ❌ Incorrect imports
import { handleNumericInput } from "./HandleNumericInput";  // Wrong file name
import { HandleNumericInput } from "./handleNumericInput";  // Wrong function name
```

## Test File Naming
- Test files must follow the same camelCase convention
- Test file name should be: `functionName.test.ts`

### Test File Examples
```
src/utils/handleNumericInput.test.ts
src/utils/parseNumber.test.ts
src/utils/convertToEuro.test.ts
```

## Enforcement
- All new utility functions must follow these conventions
- When refactoring existing utilities, rename files to match function names
- Update all imports when renaming utility files
- Run tests after renaming to ensure all imports are updated

## Benefits
- **Consistency**: Makes codebase predictable and easier to navigate
- **Discoverability**: File name immediately indicates what function it exports
- **Tooling**: Improves IDE auto-imports and refactoring support
- **Maintenance**: Reduces confusion and makes code reviews more efficient

## Migration Examples

### Before Refactoring
```
src/utils/HandleNumericInput.ts  // ❌ PascalCase
export function handleNumericInput() { ... }
```

### After Refactoring
```
src/utils/handleNumericInput.ts  // ✅ camelCase
export function handleNumericInput() { ... }
```

